Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "Application Insights SDK fails to add config (Need help getting more logs out of NuGet client tools)" (#9448) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
Application Insights SDK publishes this package: https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ApplicationInsights.Web/ .
During installation, this package should add an "applicationinsights.config" file to the customer's application.
This works for most of our users but a small subset of users do not get this file added.

When I run the command `Install-Package Microsoft.ApplicationInsights.Web -Verbose` I see the log:
> Added file 'ApplicationInsights.config' to project 'WebApplication28'.

Our customers have shared verbose logs showing no errors and no attempt to add this config file to their projects.
https://github.com/microsoft/ApplicationInsights-dotnet/issues/1337




## Details about Problem

NuGet product used: Package Manager Console

NuGet version: 5.5.0

dotnet.exe --version (if appropriate): 3.1.201

VS version (if appropriate): 16.5.4

OS version (i.e. win10 v1607 (14393.321)): Windows 10 v1909 (Build 18363.778)

## Detailed repro steps so we can see the same problem

We don't currently have a repo. I'm looking for guidance to collect more logs and maybe hone in on a repro.


## Other suggested things

### Verbose Logs

Please include verbose logs (NuGet.exe <COMMAND> -verbosity detailed | dotnet.exe <COMMAND> --verbosity diag | etc...)

### Sample Project

Very helpful if you can zip a project and paste into this issue!

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue ".snupkg Files created and pushed but NuGet not downloading them" (#9456) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
Hey Guys,

me and a friend are developing a framework together and we are publishing nuget packages. We have now added creation of .snupkg files. They are also pushed to NuGet without problems. But when we use our packages Visual Studio is not able to step into the code.

I have already set "Enable just my Code" to false and checked if the NuGet symbol server is also referenced in the settings. But it does not work.

We have added the following to our csproj files to generate a .snupkg:
```
<IncludeSymbols>true</IncludeSymbols>
<SymbolPackageFormat>snupkg</SymbolPackageFormat>
```

I also tried clearing the nuget cache and restoring all packages. But the .snupkg files are never downloaded. Do I miss something here?

Thanks for your time and effort!

Kind Regards,
Daniel

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "[Feature] Allow `dotnet add package` command to add a reference without setting the version " (#7785) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
_From @alirezajm on February 12, 2019 22:12_

Allow adding package references via the cli without it setting the version in the project file.
This is useful when a **Directory.build.targets** file is present and it is used to manage package versions.

## Feature behavior
Considering there is a Directory.Build.targes file present, containing the following
`<PackageReference Update="Microsoft.Orleans.Core" Version="2.1.2" />` 
running
`dotnet add package Microsoft.Orleans.Core --use-targets-version`
will add
 `<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Orleans.Core" />` in the .csproj file.
All compatibility checks are intact.

If no reference is present in the .targets file, it should result in an error. Or maybe add an `<PackageReference Include="...` item.

Additional feature:
Enable adding and removing packages to .targets file. This of course is a bit more complex as currently **dotnet add package** command adds/upgrades package references, which will not work quite well with .target files

_Copied from original issue: dotnet/cli#10757_

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "Deprecating TLS 1.0 and 1.1 on NuGet.org – Stage 1" (#42) at NuGet/Announcements
Events.RelatedBody:
## NuGet.org will temporarily remove support for TLS 1.0/1.1 on February 26, 2020

We plan to temporarily remove support for TLS 1.0/1.1 across 3 time slots in a 24 hour period, for 4 hours each, to ensure overlap with normal working hours across the globe. If you discover that you are impacted and cannot identify a workaround, please open an issue on the NuGet Gallery GitHub repo.

Read this blog post to learn more and to identify the test slot time in your time zone - https://devblogs.microsoft.com/nuget/deprecating-tls-1-0-and-1-1-on-nuget-org-stage-1/
